And the docker-compose settings:

```
hygieia-jira-feature-collector:

container_name: hygieia-jira

  - JIRA_ISSUE_TYPE_ID=267
  - JIRA_SPRINT_DATA_FIELD_NAME=customfield_14290
  - JIRA_EPIC_FIELD_NAME=customfield_15590
```
column12: 219075419 @amp5208 help! tabladrum 219456849 @Matschick , Thank you for reaching out regarding your JiraFeatureCollector issue. It appears that you are missing several properties that should be passed through as environment variables for this to run in Docker. Also, one of your properties is incorrect. As of the incorrect property, _JIRA_ISSUE_TYPE_, this should be a string variable (non-oblique ID). For issue-type-story, it should be just Story Also, you appear to be missing overrides for, at minimum, the field mapping properties. Full explanation for using field mappings and examples can be found at this issue's comment: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/276#issuecomment-196324494 Please verify your property configurations and let us know if you nee further assistance. amp5208 277306252 Closed. satishc1

3. Open Hygieia and see the results

This PR includes the following changes:
- added a new section in the cloud view for displaying VPC/Subnet ip utilization
- added separate controllers for the ip utilization views
- increased the cloud widget size in caponechatops.html to col-xs-12

Styling work is not yet done, but the overall functionality is completed.

column5: Calculate volume usage, display acocunt number as part of summary/detail tag information
Added filtering based on config tag choices, searchable tags in filtering, some performance enhancements

I wonder if ... did someone solve this problem?
 oshingc
233225809 They use some key for login . I also wasnt able to make it work and did a small workaround for this . Add the below code in your class DefaultBitbucketServerClient.java after line no 96.

```
if (decryptedPassword.equals("")) {
        decryptedPassword = "Yourpassword";
        repo.setUserId("YourUsername");
      }
```

But ofcourse not a nice way . Better understand how the key works.

218409740 The problem is that I use two versions of hygieia :)
To solve this problem :
- empty the cache => docker : 
  
  # Delete all containers
  
  sudo docker rm $(sudo docker ps -a -q)
  
  # Delete all images
  
  sudo docker rmi $(sudo docker images -q)
- delete mongodb collections

column2: Using Hygiea as one tool across your enterprise for single view into your env, you can measure your progress for SDLC for your projects projects hosted on GIT. Metrics such as Pulls created by day, or Issues, average times resolving issues/PRs, Top contributors, their ORGs (external data integration -interfaces will be provided along with a sample implementation) to measure how much of the contributions are coming from your own enterprise versus the rest - and such. Please feel free to offer more ideas as you see or partner with us to implement this. There is a Pull Request (#540) open on which the development is happening. The PR work is complete and is awaiting approval by repo owners. The size of the work is pretty significant - so there might be a slight delay in approvals for the merge request. Hygieia provides hooks into GIT as well along with Subversion and others but what this PR aims to do is explain that hook - which is just Commits for now - into multiple Views that would include developers, pulls, issues, organizational structures of our org, and metrics around repos. Also, one of the changes that’s introduced with this PR is to take the git org name as input instead of git repo name. Basically hit git against an org name and provide metrics against all repos of that org combined. Where applicable, the repo name is shown as well on the screens however. In the very near future, we will actually take in Collection of org names and provide a roll view that’s applicable at higher levels - subject to app owner's interest. Here are the same screen shots of the template - with more widgets to come and UI enhancement to show detailed view on click - each of these widgets would take org name as input - for now. Now - what do we want to know from GI. These are what I thought made sense the most - Who is providing the code - meaning which developer or LOB is providing the code so that sort of helps you organize your teams accordingly. May be you want to see how your internal orgs are getting comfortable contributing to other repos of ANOTHER org, or how teams from outside of your department are contributing to your repos etc. May be the word that we might be looking for is “InnerSourcing” and this helps managers observe the metrics on how this inner sourcing is going - it’s similar to you contributing to open source but here you are contributing to apps outside of your area - may be that’s your passion or hobby or strong point etc - what ever the case may be - your org would still benefit b/c you will end up breaking your organization silo’s - Secondly -From git, You may want to know how your development pipe line is looking. Are PRs aging appropriately, are issues getting CLOSED promptly -What are the issues or PRs that took the longest - What are the issues that are still open for the longest etc We can also add which developer from your org is contributing to what repo - but that may be a stretch at this time. There may be other metrics that I can’t think of at the moment - but here’s a little mention about the data. Well, GIT is your source for code data but the other important element is - developer data. In my case, I have some API’s which would provide me the people data such as Name, Manager, Business leads, IT leads etc and for every pull or issues that the collector pulls for that day/run, it uses these APIs to find that data and store them. That’s important b/c people change departments and it’s important to capture those contributor metrics right at that time. If you org has datasources that would keep such snapshot data, then you don’t need to implement that but if you don’t, you need to implement an interface that I included in this PR and I also checked in a Default Dummy client that you can use as a reference. Now, let’s get to the sample widgets this issue (PR #540) would be solving for. These would tell you who your top contributors are so you can tell how you need to configure your team - may be call them a loosely configured team called “core committers” - or core developers etc - this is where you look for that. If you want to see which Line of Business or department or exec is contributing to your apps, this is here you look. This is for the last 90 days - and 90 days should be a good measure of sustained and latest interest of others in your apps. These four will give us a glimpse of trend of interest of PRs and Issues on your apps. A downward trend shows declining intent or upward trend shows you the increasing interest.The number of distinct developers in the first half of the quarter to the same on the second half shows how the developer base is expanding. The more the merrier. In this chart, we seem to have the almost equal number of distinct developers working on this organization - if are actually working on expanding this - you need to see more count of (distinct) developers on the last 45 days than the first 45 days of the 90 day period you are looking for. The next two shows us the “aging chart of PRs and issues” - You can see the top 5 in the table below.This is basically the days between closing or merging and opening of a PR or an issue divided by number that are closed that day. A good source of info for those looking to find why the pipeline isn't fast enough - or what PRs/issue are taking the longest. Click on each of the chart points to see what there are - or the table below shows the top 5 any way. The last one is the Commit - actually this came out of the box - I didn’t do any changes here - it is just telling me there is some sustained action going on in the apps. You can click on each of the chart points to see what those commit are ![Uploading CommitsDetails.png…]() Now - this is more like a beginning of what I think we can add to this - the entries that are commented (below pic) are what I think should be added to give us additional metrics into finding what your most popular repo is, where your developers are contributing to from with in your orgs, latest pulls by repo etc. I focussed mainly on the UI to convey what I added - but I added just two domain objects in Core and two JPA finders in api - and corresponding methods on GIT Collector. What I am requesting is an acceptance of this PR so I can start working on one widget at a time - and even come back and refactor the code to see if we some how reuse the code more efficiently etc. Please review PR#540 where I implemented what I presented above and merge

Are there plans to make the jenkins plugin compatible with Jenkins Pipeline?
https://github.com/jenkinsci/pipeline-plugin/blob/master/COMPATIBILITY.md

Having said that, I would actually prefer a non plugin method of publishing build data from the Jenkins Pipeline DSL, even if it's simple curl via the shell command.

column2:
**Narrative:**

As a user of the Jira Feature Widget, I want to be able to use the Feature widget for Kanban boards, so that my Kanban teams can better understand where they are currently regarding intent.

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [x] Kanban (sprintless) boards in Jira show valid data on the Hygieia Feature Widget

**Use Case:**

```
GIVEN:  A sprintless Jira Kanban board
WHEN:  An issue type story is created with Remaining Estimate filled out
THEN:  The issue type story shows up in the Hygieia Feature Widget with the Remaining Estimate values
```
column5: Request:  Feature Widget does not support Jira Kanban

209708852 Artifact Directory - with respect to your workspace, where the artifacts (such as .jar) file are
Artifact Filename pattern - "*.jar" for example
Artifact Group - com.capitalone.dashboard for example
Artifact Version - "2.0.0" for example - if the version is in the filename such as "core-2.0.0.jar", it will automatically derive the version.

> <dockerMachineName>${docker.machine.name}</dockerMachineName> - default
> <dockerTlsVerify>${docker.tls.verify}</dockerTlsVerify> - 1
> <dockerToolboxInstallPath>${docker.toolbox.install.path}</dockerToolboxInstallPath> - C:\Program Files\Docker Toolbox
> <dockerCertPath>${docker.cert.path}</dockerCertPath> - C:\Users\96446.docker\machine\machines\default

`Unsupported protocol tcp.`

`Connection refused`

So by putting `http` and port `8080` I think I am one step closer. 

Can you do let me know how to proceed from this error?

215736672 @aryasunny, Thank you for following-up with your connection issues to Jira via Hygieia.  However, the error you are getting I have never seen during use of our collectors; it would seem to me that Jira (the remote host) or some abstraction infrastructure layer within your company (e.g., an API gateway) is rejecting your request for some reason.  Please validate the following, assuming that your properties are correctly configured:
- Ensure that you have your remote Jira web certificate installed on your JDK's keystore; _Note:_  If you are deploying to a non-production region that is blocked from communicating to production domains, you will not be able to communication to that Jira instance; ask your Jira admin for a non-production instance of Jira.
- Ensure that your Jira admin has configured Jira to accept basic authentication (e.g., nosso)
- Ensure that your Jira admin is not disallowing API connectivity from end-users
- Validate with your Jira admin the state of your Jira Sessions as they come in from Hygieia
- If you have an abstracted infrastructure layer (e.g., an API gateway), please validate you are meeting that layer's communication contract (e.g. header, WSDL, WADL, API, etc.).  You may have to even transform the messages coming out of Hygieia to meet your company's transaction requirements through that abstracted layer.

After validating these things, please reply with your findings/status, and I can provide more assistance.

208011541 thanks topo for replying.

So this is what I did.

I created an application.properties file and placed it here --> 
/github-scm-collector/src/main/resources/application.properties

After this I ran this command from inside target folder of github-collector module --> 
java -jar github-scm-collector-2.0.0-SNAPSHOT.jar

my collector module runs successfully and I am able to configure the widget now.

column2:
Is there a document that clearly explains the technology/tools being used in hygieia.

My understanding is that 
There is a collector that runs and collects stats and inserts into MongoD.
A rest API is used to fetch this data from the MongoD
AngularJS is being used in UI module which invokes the REST APIs to render the view.
(Question - why installation of NodeJS is a requirement for UI module)

Is there any document that explains the code flow starting from collector to REST API to the AngularJS view rendering.

P.S - I am newbie in this world of Spring,AngularJS and related technologies.

column2:
Do you have plans to support other CI systems than Jenkins?  Examples: Go, TeamCity.

The issue title includes "API" to cover either you building out that support, or providing an API for others to hook into Hygieia with alternate CI systems.

The HudsonClient interface in the build collector is, obviously, specific to Jenkins.

column2:
This PR is to fix a bug whereby commits can be orphaned in the commit stage of the product pipeline widget.

Here is the scenario:
1. A (team) dashboard exists with a configured SCM widget (using the Github webhook push method)
2. The same dashboard does **NOT** have a build widget configured
3. A new commit (call it commit A) is pushed to the Github repo
4. The build widget is then added to the team dashboard
5. A new product dashboard is created that references the team dashboard.
6. Commit A is displayed in the commit stage and never moves to subsequent stages.

This PR proposes to fix the bug by not adding commits to the pipeline of a team dashboard if there is no build widget configured.
column5: Fix for orphaned commits in commit stage of pipeline when no build configured

column2: I am having trouble getting the custom field value for "feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName". I ran the rest api against a jira issue that has super issue as EPIC. Please help here.
column5: I am having trouble getting the custom field value for "feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName". I ran the rest api against a jira issue that has super issue as EPIC. Please help here.
column12:
200498932 @amp5208 - can you please take a look?
 tabladrum
201703208 @roykaushik07 , Thank you for reaching out regarding the jiraEpicIdFieldName.  To get this field name, you have to perform the following API actions manually against your Jira instance, using a sample Jira issue that has a super issue as Epic, as you have indicated:

```
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "super story" or "epic" back-end ID,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's epic ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has a super issue (e.g., epic) tied to it; your custom field name describes the
# epic value you expect to see, and is the only field that does this for a given issue:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_10400
```

Essentially, you have to use the Jira API to look up an existing issue that has a super issue tied to it, then Ctrl-F on the output for that super issue reference; the resulting field's name (usually starting with "customfield_") is the value that needs to be placed on this property.  This field ID is different for every installation of Jira, and different on most regions, given your internal Jira deployment plan.

The documentation above can be found as comments in the embedded properties file sample.  Let me know if you are still having this issue after trying to acquire the epic field name using the above instructions.  Note:  This question was also raised and answered in the following comment within an open GitHub issue; linking for clarity:  https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/276#issuecomment-172060522
 amp5208
206171769 @roykaushik07  Better copy the result of the above mentioned URL into some json editor & navigate/search. You can easily find the value.
 smsuresh
207591200 @roykaushik07 , @smsuresh  is correct:  That is the best option for retrieving the value at this time:  Save the output from the Jira response to a JSON file, use a JSON linter to format or "beautify" the JSON, and look for the field name and value pair.

Please also respond once you can confirm this issue is resolved.
 amp5208

198505015 I too am trying to get this setup on a Windows Server and am running into several issues.

I've been following the steps in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/Setup.md

I am unclear on how to build the API layer. The instructions are exactly clear on what steps are necessary to build the API layer. "Please click on the link below to learn about how to build and run the API layer."

How exactly am I supposed to run the following command?
"Run mvn install to package the collector into an executable JAR file."
https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/master/api
 ianceicys
198552831 I am not too familiar with Windows. But overall these should be the steps (will publish detailed steps once I get some help from some other developers)
1. Install Maven on Windows (http://www.mkyong.com/maven/how-to-install-maven-in-windows/)
2. Install node etc (http://blog.teamtreehouse.com/install-node-js-npm-windows)
3. clone the hygieia repo
4. from the Hygieia directory, run "mvn clean package" 
5. API and other collectors will have target folder and you will find the jar file in there to run.

If you are behind corporate proxy, read these two:
https://maven.apache.org/guides/mini/guide-proxies.html
http://jjasonclark.com/how-to-setup-node-behind-web-proxy/

Let me know if these help/dont help.

For Windows server, http://httpd.apache.org/docs/current/platform/windows.html this help in running an apache server where you can drop the UI/dist folder. 
The API can run as a service (there is a way to run jar as windows service; may be this one: http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-daemon/procrun.html) I will have to confirm.

column2: Currently with the VersionOne feature collector, if you are successfully able to communicate with VersionOne, but your access token is not authorized, VersionOne does not send a standard HTTP 403 response; instead, it responds with a custom message body {"error":"Unauthorized"}. Currently, the VersionOneFeatureCollector will interpret this as a ClassCastException, because the response is not in the standard JSONArray format normally provided by a successful VersionOne API response. This fix will determine if the response was validly responding with corrupted data, or if it is a custom VersionOne Not Authorized response. This will log at error level accordingly at runtime.
column12:
195537022 Yes, but the exception is not verbose, and does not accurately inform the user that it was their authentication that failed.  You can replicate this scenario by taking the current master of Hygieia's VersionOneFeatureCollector, then use a bad VersionOne authentication token... it will give you a nondescript "ClassCastException" error, resulting in a JSONArray casting error message.  It is incorrect - my fix shows instead that you received a VersionOne unauthorized exception.

I can remove the global Exception catch here.  Is that acceptable?  Remember:  This quick fix does not include the PMD fixes planned for next iteration (which would include fixes arbitration NullPointerException catches, etc.).
 amp5208

column5: JIRA configuration only getting 1 sprint data
column12:
195447480 I verified that customfield_10300 is that for all sprints when going to /rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name] for an issue from each sprint. Still unsure why the dashboard is only displaying information for only 1 sprint. Any ideas? aleitner 195475744 @aleitner , Thank you for your question. The way the collectors for the Feature Widget are currently configured, it assumes the following Jira configuration: 1 active project (that would align to a "team"), 1 active sprint, and many issues-type-story aligned to that active sprint. Is this your current configuration, or does this assumption not hold for your implementation of Jira? There is a similar issue posted questioning the Hygieia configuration with regard to Kanban boards here: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/290. Please also reference that for details. EDIT: I would also suggest reducing the page-size in your property file (preferably, to 50), as we have seen connectivity issues with large page sizes - currently unrelated to this question, however amp5208 195504772 Our Jira is 1 active project, multiple teams, multiple sprints(1 for each team), and many issues assigned to each sprint. So is the collector getting the data like so: `for each feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName count all feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName with application.properties statuses` some of them numbers aren't lining up correctly. aleitner 195540273 There is a disparity in our current design assumptions and your implementation then, unfortunately. Are you using a custom "Team" field to differential teams within the project? If so, there is currently an open enhancement request on this particular item: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/82. Our current implementation is more like this: 
GIVEN: 1 active Jira project AND 1 active sprint
WHEN:  A feature widget is configured for a given project
THEN:  Data is displayed accumulating all active stories for a given project in the active
       sprint WHERE active sprint is operationally defined as any sprints on stories that
       have a start/end date which spans "now"
Hope this helps. amp5208 251400298 Closed. Use the latest codebase. satishc1

column2: The Jenkins collector is unable to traverse within folders so it is unable to see any jobs within a folder. It marks the folder as a job within the Hygieia UI.
column5: Jenkins collector does not support folders which will significantly reduce the usability of the collector. The collector is a preferred method over the Jenkins plugin for large deployments as the plugin requires modifying every job
column12:
222929018 I have the similar problem. The Jenkins collector picks up the list of jobs which are at the top level. For instance, if I have got JobA, JobB, FolderA/AnotherJobA and FolderB/AnotherJobB then the Jenkins collector shows JobA, JobB, FolderA and FolderB in the list when configuring the widget.
 SachinKSingh28
224023242 From what I can see the jenkins collector doesn't support recursive folder search. You can kind of work around this by creating multiple entries in the configuration, BUT we have an issue with this on our setup.

So, you could do this in the properties file
jenkins.servers[0]=http://jenkins.company.com/
jenkins.servers[1]=http://jenkins.company.com/FolderA
jenkins.servers[2]=http://jenkins.company.com/FolderB

You'll then get a list of jobs that are at the root, and in FolderA and Folder B.

A couple of issues with this tho. In our case the jobs are named the same...
jenkins.servers[0]=http://jenkins.company.com/commitStage
jenkins.servers[1]=http://jenkins.company.com/FolderA/commitStage
jenkins.servers[2]=http://jenkins.company.com/FolderB/commitStage

So, in the UI I just see commitStage listed 3 times with no indication as to which is which.

Also, if you are using the docker compose file, the script (jenkins-build-properties-builder.sh) doesn't support multiple entries.

An ideal solution would traverse all folders and provide a UI that makes it easy to differentiate between jobs with the same name.

The other issue we have is that our jenkins instances have 100s, if not 1000s, of folders/jobs. So what we really need on the UI is a better way to find the job.

Fixed the Sonar build and updated docker containers for all modules.
- # 337 - Add Docker Containers for stash/svn/udeploy/versionone & cleanup docker file for jenkins test instance (5 days ago) Jim Zucker
- # 363 - updated the jacoco plugin to the current version (8 days ago) Jim Zucker
- # 364 Upgrade maven-compiler-plugin to 3.5.1 rev
-  #365 Jacoco not running for all subproject -  Fixed jacoco/Sonar runs.  There is one outstanding issue and sonar is skipped for the git and stash collectors(ref #370)  
-  #351 - PMD Warning - Overridable method called during object construction - had to fix them in this branch as build was failing after compiler upgrade (9 days ago) Jim Zucker

It is safe to commit but I need help testing these containers: 
jira
version-one
subversion
udeploy

if somebody can give me details what to setup I am happy to test and I can create esc environments for them like I did for Jenkins & Sonar.

In the new dashboard where will we show the following data
1. artifact 
2. deployment (i guess widget exists)
3. test results
column5: About Artiactory, deployment, and test results
column12:
193826439 Can someone respond to this one please... 
 softwareklinic
193829797 Please see the Hygieia 2.0 documentation for reference: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/Hygieia2.md

Test Results:
- If you publish (via Jenkins hygieia plugin) the cucumber test results, you can select those jenkins jobs in your Quality widget: Functional Test: 
  ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6014941/13606509/287695ee-e51a-11e5-8379-e19aabb8fed2.png)

Deployment:
The widget already exist. Again, if you publish your deployment results via Jenkins plugin, they will show up in the deployment widget:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6014941/13606605/8b34982a-e51a-11e5-820b-054129189adb.png)

Artifacts:
There is no separate widget for Artifact. However, if you publish Artifact info via Jenkins plugin, Hygieia will successfully link your code -> build -> artifact -> deployment "pipeline" in the Hygieia 2.0 product dashboard (see Hygieia 2.0 documentation)

column2:
With Hygieia 2.0, you can publish Build, Sonar Analysis, Artifact Info, Deployment (if using Jenkins to deploy), Cucumber Test Results from Jenkins to Hygieia. Use the latest Jenkins Plugin (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/master/hygieia-jenkins-plugin).

For Github webhook, the  payload url should be set to: http://hygieia-base-url/api/commit/github/v3
Select to publish just the "push" events. 

With the above two new features, you will not need to run github collector, jenkins build collector, sonar collector and jenkins cucumber test collector.
column5: Now you can use Jenkins Plugin and Github Webhook

Sent from my iPhone

On Feb 29, 2016, at 10:01 PM, tabladrum <notifications@github.com<mailto:notifications@github.com>> wrote:

With Hygieia 2.0, you can publish Build, Sonar Analysis, Artifact Info, Deployment (if using Jenkins to deploy), Cucumber Test Results from Jenkins to Hygieia. Use the latest Jenkins Plugin (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/master/hygieia-jenkins-plugin).

For Github webhook, the payload url should be set to: http://hygieia-base-url/api/commit/github/v3
Select to publish just the "push" events.

With the above two new features, you will not need to run github collector, jenkins build collector, sonar collector and jenkins cucumber test collector.

—

This solved my issue with getting 2.0.0 working. The api and UI are not connected

        at org.apache.maven.surefire.junit4.JUnit4Provider.execute(JUnit4Provider.java:264) [surefire-junit4-2.17.jar:2.17]
        at org.apache.maven.surefire.junit4.JUnit4Provider.executeTestSet(JUnit4Provider.java:153) [surefire-junit4-2.17.jar:2.17]
        at org.apache.maven.surefire.junit4.JUnit4Provider.invoke(JUnit4Provider.java:124) [surefire-junit4-2.17.jar:2.17]
        at org.apache.maven.surefire.booter.ForkedBooter.invokeProviderInSameClassLoader(ForkedBooter.java:200) [surefire-booter-2.17.jar:2.17]
        at org.apache.maven.surefire.booter.ForkedBooter.runSuitesInProcess(ForkedBooter.java:153) [surefire-booter-2.17.jar:2.17]
        at org.apache.maven.surefire.booter.ForkedBooter.main(ForkedBooter.java:103) [surefire-booter-2.17.jar:2.17]

This is caused by an assumption in EmbeddedMongoDBRule.java that assumes the HTTP_PROXY URL has a userinfo portion:

```
            URL proxyUrl = new URL(proxy);

            // Case for Proxy authentication required
            try {
                StringTokenizer tokenizedUrl = new StringTokenizer(proxyUrl
                        .**getUserInfo**().toString(), ":");
                if (tokenizedUrl.hasMoreTokens()) {
```

The userinfo portion of the proxy URL is optional, so without it we pop the NPE.

This error is back when trying to run:
mvn sonar:sonar -Dsonar.host.url=http://$(docker-machine ip default):9000 -Dsonar.jdbc.url="jdbc:h2:tcp://$(docker-machine ip default)/sonar"

```
       [ERROR] Failed to execute goal org.sonarsource.scanner.maven:sonar-maven-plugin:3.0.1:sonar (default-cli) on project Hygieia: Unable to read /Users/jaz/work/Hygieia/api/target/jacoco.exec: Incompatible version 1007. -> [Help 1]
```

I did see a comment on a ticket that the version of Jacoco was purposefully moved back to 0.7.5.xxx

I tried 0.7.6.201602180812 (new version, but I still get this error).

I found this ticket on jacoco: https://github.com/jacoco/jacoco/issues/315  bottom line is: "This is not a bug on JaCoCo side, but intentional change for binary dump file as consequence of #310 - see changelog http://www.eclemma.org/jacoco/trunk/doc/changes.html
Third-party integrations, which use this binary dump file (such as SonarQube) should be updated, or previous version of JaCoCo should be used for them."

**I created a issue for the sonar team: https://github.com/SonarSource/sonar-maven/issues/4

217782164 I am using latest version of Hygieia and facing same issue of Forbidden access with GitHub private repository. Is there way to solve this??

218020547 Hi,
You need to add in your UserID and API key in application .properites file like below.

github.UserId=p710231
github.key=XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXc1

Then modify DefaultGitHubClient.java and force the response string to fetch the password from properties file

```
                            //ResponseEntity<String> response = makeRestCall(queryUrlPage, settings.getUserId(), decryptedPassword);
                            ResponseEntity<String> response = makeRestCall(queryUrlPage, settings.getUserId(), settings.getKey());
```

Thanks,

We need to add containers for these collectors to finish the docker setup.  We should create them and also add optional test servers that we can use for demo and automated testing (test servers are under $ROOT/docker, today there is a jenkins and a sonar server you can optionally build for testing).

I plan to add them to the compose file commented out, people can enable them by adding them to their override file.

product-product-collector (this looks empty right now, so now action)
stash-scm-collector
subversion-scm-collector
udeploy-deployment-collector
versionone-feature-collector

205342554 @gitfan89 , It appears that two things are going on here which would affect your error response:
- You are receiving a 403 HTTP response, meaning that your SSL certificate keystore has not been updated correctly with your remove Jira instance
- You still have some property configuration issues

For the first issue, please ensure that you 1) can reach the Jira instance via HTTPS from your Hygieia region and 2) ensure that your Java & OS-level keystore has been updated with the Jira certificate correctly.  To do this, try to telnet or cURL from your Hygieia server to the Jira server - failures would indicate a network firewall or security issue.  Secondly, use openssh or Java Keytool to validate your Java keystore for the Jira certificate presence; also be sure to add the certificate to your OS-level keystore to ensure no break in communication for Linux/Unix systems (the method for OS-level certificate keystore updating is different between each distribution).

Regarding issue 2, see below for an updated/cleaned property file list based on what you have provided me in the text file; please replace your property file with the fixed one below (update with your credentials, etc.):

215738861 @aryasunny , Thank you for following-up.  The proxy configuration noted within this property file is not Jira specific necessarily; if you have a proxy, you must fill out the proxy configuration section of the properties (currently, the JiraFeatureCollector does not implement system environment configuration for proxy, i.e., HTTP_PROXY).

Regarding your specific error, if you do not have an authentication proxy, your Jira property configuration for the proxy-specific settings should be the following (assuming a proxy IP):

``` properties
# Jira Connection Details - Proxy is NOT just a 'Jira specific proxy' - this is your global enterprise proxy
feature.jiraProxyUrl=http://192.168.1.1
feature.jiraProxyPort=4000
```

205342554 @gitfan89 , It appears that two things are going on here which would affect your error response:
- You are receiving a 403 HTTP response, meaning that your SSL certificate keystore has not been updated correctly with your remove Jira instance
- You still have some property configuration issues

For the first issue, please ensure that you 1) can reach the Jira instance via HTTPS from your Hygieia region and 2) ensure that your Java & OS-level keystore has been updated with the Jira certificate correctly.  To do this, try to telnet or cURL from your Hygieia server to the Jira server - failures would indicate a network firewall or security issue.  Secondly, use openssh or Java Keytool to validate your Java keystore for the Jira certificate presence; also be sure to add the certificate to your OS-level keystore to ensure no break in communication for Linux/Unix systems (the method for OS-level certificate keystore updating is different between each distribution).

P.S- I am giving the IP address in the property feature.jiraProxyUrl. I understand that it is expecting proxy URL in this format --> http://JIRAPROXY.com

215738861 @aryasunny , Thank you for following-up.  The proxy configuration noted within this property file is not Jira specific necessarily; if you have a proxy, you must fill out the proxy configuration section of the properties (currently, the JiraFeatureCollector does not implement system environment configuration for proxy, i.e., HTTP_PROXY).

Regarding your specific error, if you do not have an authentication proxy, your Jira property configuration for the proxy-specific settings should be the following (assuming a proxy IP):

``` properties
# Jira Connection Details - Proxy is NOT just a 'Jira specific proxy' - this is your global enterprise proxy
feature.jiraProxyUrl=http://192.168.1.1
feature.jiraProxyPort=4000
```

Please let me know if you have any additional questions.

column2:
This pull request is the culmination of a 4 week development effort to build a product dashboard to display pipeline health across multiple teams. While this is the major feature delivered by this PR, there are also numerous enhancements and bug fixes, including:
## Enhancements
- Ability to create a product dashboard
- Enhance list view to improve filtering and make product dashboards visually distinct
- Ability to add/remove a team to a product dashboard
- Ability reorder the team rows in a product dashboard via drag and drop
- Ability to view pipeline health (i.e Quality) summary metrics for each team on the product dashboard
- Ability to view commit details for a given pipeline stage
- Ability to view quality details for a given team row
- New API to allow pushing of commits to Hygieia via GitHub webhooks
- New API to allow pushing of build data
- New API to allow pushing of binary artifacts
- New API to allow pushing of deploy data
- New API to allow pushing of quality data
- New API to allow pushing of test result data
- Introduction of a client-side database (Dexie) to reduce the amount data transferred from server to client on every request
## Bug fixes
- Fixes #265 by simplifying and improving the UI gulp build process
- Fixes #113 by creating a global config object in the UI to allow command line args to bypass defaults
- Fixes #275 by upgrading to the latest version of the Chartist library and fixing the existing charts accordingly
- Fixes #170 and #274 via creation of new Chartist plugin

---

You can view, comment on, or merge this pull request online at:

  https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/328

Commit Summary
-   allow users to reorder teams on product dashboard
-   default modal to show close button
-   split data processing logic into multiple files
-   Changed how we are pulling mapped names by fetching widget options, shoving them into a case insensitive tree map and using that. Not elegant, but not sure of a better way. The widget options has everything forced to lowercase by the UI before persistence. Also added null safety to pipeline service in case an environment isn't mapped. The treemap doesn't handle nulls for the get.
-   Merge branch 'hygieia-2' of https://github.com/singlestone/Hygieia into hygieia-2
-   catch less errors
-   pmd cleanup
-   Adding comments throughout.
-   More comments around the event listeners. Removed the suppression PMD errors on EnvironmentComponentEventListener as well.
-   prevent js error on initial product dashboard load
-   Merge branch 'hygieia-2' of https://github.com/singlestone/Hygieia into hygieia-2
-   add new form group directive to enable easier implementation of consistent validation throughout the framework. updated existing validations
-   validation message when missing dashboard title
-   change stage cells to show two std deviations in the +- part
-   Simple test for the method on Dashboard that fetches the environment mappings. This exposed a bug when the pipeline isn't configured. Fixed said NPE case.
-   allow dashboard to scroll horizontally
-   Merge branch 'hygieia-2' of https://github.com/singlestone/Hygieia into hygieia-2
-   show std deviation even if it's 0
-   double std deviation before calculating minutes. this way a 50 sec std deviation will show as +-1 min instead of 0
-   rename quality detail
-   Creates pipeline if pipeline doesn't exist.
-   Merge branch 'hygieia-2' of https://github.com/singlestone/Hygieia into hygieia-2
-   refactor product data methods to services
-   added url as reference for Dexie versioning
-   Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/hygieia-2.0' into hygieia-2
-   Removed duplicate dependency declaration to resolve maven warning messages.

183373172 @BeenaMP - I believe the error is related to your build env,potentially your JAVA install.  The error is a connectivity issue between maven and the repo to download the plugins.  If you google "sun.security.validator.ValidatorEx
on: PKIX path building failed: sun.security.provider.certpath.SunCertPathBuilderException: unable to find valid certification path to requested target"  you will find a bunch of hits related to this error, you will have to sift through them to fix your env.

220381172 @jimzucker , Not including the Jira certificate would cause problems, but not this one; I would expect it to throw x509 or PKIX Certificate errors at the Java runtime level. You will need that installed to your Java keystore regardless, however. Just to check my theory, can you try to cURL an authenticated Jira API request to your Jira implementation from your computer? I believe that your command should ultimately look like this: ``` bash # 1) This will give the HTTP code response back; it will not return the actual message: curl --cacert /path/to/your/jira/cert.pem -I -X GET --header "Content-Type: application/json" https://$JIRA_USER:$JIRA_PASS@stratengllc.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/VALIDSTORY-12 # You may need to include the following parameter flag if your Jira certificate is signed using TLS: --tlsv1 # 2) Then, try and run this version of the cURL command; let me know which one worked and which one did not: curl --cacert /path/to/your/jira/cert.pem -I -X GET --header "Authorization: Basic [base64encoded_user:pass]" --header "Content-Type: application/json" https://stratengllc.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/VALIDSTORY-12 # Note: You may also have to included your proxy authorization header explicitly if behind an auth-proxy. Here is the parameter syntax to add to the above calls: --header "Proxy-Authorization: Basic [base64encoded_user:pass]" ``` It is worth mentioning that I also had trouble authenticating using the second option which uses an explicit authorization header. The issue was related to Mac's implementation of base64, which seems to add something invisible to the ASCII result; after re-encoding with a different tool, I received valid base64. I would suggest re-validating your base64 _not_ using the base64 encoder on Mac. If that gets denied for the same HTTP 401 error you were seeing in Hygieia, this is a large problem of your implementation of Jira not allowing for basic authentication. You would ultimately have 2 options at that point: 1) Contact your Jira admin and ask them to enable _nosso_ option of authentication; 2) Update the JiraFeatureCollector to use token-based authentication (token or OAuth2.0). The latter may be the only option. Please let me know how this goes for you. **_EDIT:**_ _For grammatical errors..._ amp5208 220402038 Thanks this strategy worked. The real issue was I was passing emailaddress:password, seems the API requires you use the real userid, email does not work! Thank you for your patience and contribution!! amp5208 220623892 For those that come here after the merged fix is implemented, it is important to note that the "ghost" `\n` return carriage that is included in a base64 encoded string on a Mac is avoidable easily by using the Mac implementation of `echo` correctly. Instead of the following command: ``` bash echo username:password | base64 ``` ... Use this command: ``` bash echo -n username:password | base64 ``` The `-n` option explicitly tells the Mac implementation of echo to not print the trailing new line character. amp5208 182667503 Using the clear text password for api key or the actual ali key Regards, Keyur On Feb 10, 2016, at 7:25 PM, Jim Zucker > wrote: Hi, I have been trying to get the JIRA connector to work but I can't figure out why I get a 401 error. Please advise if any progress... tonyvilliams 216956475 @tonyvilliams , Sorry to hear you are also having this issue.. @jimzucker or @tonyvilliams : Just to validate, are you able to run the collectors _without_ using Docker? 😕 e.g.: ``` bash java -jar jira-feature-collector.jar --spring.config.name=jira-feature-collector --spring.config.location=$PROPERTY_PATH/jira-feature-collector.properties ``` If you have already validated the following, I start to think this is related to Docker: - Jira credentials are accurate and have permissions to read from all projects - Jira implementation is within a non-restricted region to your Hygieia implementation - Jira public certificate has been added to the Java keystore - The following properties have been configured based on your Jira implementation: ``` bash feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName=customfield_10000 feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_10001 ``` amp5208 220065862 @amp5208 I am testing now in Eclipse, so I think that takes docker out of the picture. Also, label this issue a `Bug`; @jimzucker is going to be contributing the fix. @jimzucker : Other than this, have we answered your configuration question? Can this issue be closed after your impending code contribution? amp5208 220128677 @amp5208 lets keep this open until I get the darn thing running.. jimzucker 220142208 @amp5208 the /n was a problem but I fixed that and I still get a 401 error, line 249 gets the exceptions, any hints on how to debug this? I verified: 1. Userid/passwd - I copied them from the debugger, with the /n removed they are OK now 2. I taste the url in the browser: https://stratengllc.atlassian.net/rest/api/latest/project ![screenshot 2016-05-18 13 04 48](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/14372687/15373213/4daecd92-1cf9-11e6-8e56-bb3ed9dfda2d.png) jimzucker 220162075 hmm... that line of code is resolving your authorization header and request body against Jira's API using the Jira SDK, "claiming" the response, treating it almost like a promise. The only thing that would cause an HTTP 401: Unauthorized response here would be if your credentials are still not being mapped properly. Have you tried debugging that `client` variable to expose your message header information? I believe the problem is how you are establishing your authentication (i.e., what is being transformed and read from your property config), or your Jira implementation does not allow basic authentication (username:password). Have you verified your Jira authentication capabilities with your Jira admin? amp5208 220166344 @amp5208 I stepped into the factory.createWithBasicHttpAuthentication to verify my credentials are OK and the URL is the correct https url.. I think I need a way to verify credentials are OK in the contractor JiraDataFactoryImpl so that we can give a clear error at that time. I dont know the JIRA apis, do you have a suggestion ? jimzucker 220169521 @amp5208 I saw a thread about installing the JIRA cert in the java keystore, that is what I think is wrong, researching it now... jimzucker 220179517 @amp5208 no luck, I put this code in the constructor to ensure ids are correct, I think it has to do with certs or something, I haven't been able to figure it out yet.. any pointers? jiraServerUri = new URI("https://stratengllc.atlassian.net"); client = factory.createWithBasicHttpAuthentication(jiraServerUri, "xxxx", "xxx"); jimzucker 220381172 @jimzucker , Not including the Jira certificate would cause problems, but not this one; I would expect it to throw x509 or PKIX Certificate errors at the Java runtime level. You will need that installed to your Java keystore regardless, however. Just to check my theory, can you try to cURL an authenticated Jira API request to your Jira implementation from your computer? I believe that your command should ultimately look like this: ``` bash # 1) This will give the HTTP code response back; it will not return the actual message: curl --cacert /path/to/your/jira/cert.pem -I -X GET --header "Content-Type: application/json" https://$JIRA_USER:$JIRA_PASS@stratengllc.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/VALIDSTORY-12 # You may need to include the following parameter flag if your Jira certificate is signed using TLS: --tlsv1 # 2) Then, try and run this version of the cURL command; let me know which one worked and which one did not: curl --cacert /path/to/your/jira/cert.pem -I -X GET --header "Authorization: Basic [base64encoded_user:pass]" --header "Content-Type: application/json" https://stratengllc.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/VALIDSTORY-12 # Note: You may also have to included your proxy authorization header explicitly if behind an auth-proxy. Here is the parameter syntax to add to the above calls: --header "Proxy-Authorization: Basic [base64encoded_user:pass]" ``` It is worth mentioning that I also had trouble authenticating using the second option which uses an explicit authorization header. The issue was related to Mac's implementation of base64, which seems to add something invisible to the ASCII result; after re-encoding with a different tool, I received valid base64. I would suggest re-validating your base64 _not_ using the base64 encoder on Mac. If that gets denied for the same HTTP 401 error you were seeing in Hygieia, this is a large problem of your implementation of Jira not allowing for basic authentication. You would ultimately have 2 options at that point: 1) Contact your Jira admin and ask them to enable _nosso_ option of authentication; 2) Update the JiraFeatureCollector to use token-based authentication (token or OAuth2.0). The latter may be the only option. Please let me know how this goes for you. **_EDIT:**_ _For grammatical errors..._ amp5208 220402038 Thanks this strategy worked. The real issue was I was passing emailaddress:password, seems the API requires you use the real userid, email does not work! Here is the parameter syntax to add to the above calls: --header "Proxy-Authorization: Basic [base64encoded_user:pass]" It is worth mentioning that I also had trouble authenticating using the second option which uses an explicit authorization header. The issue was related to Mac's implementation of base64, which seems to add something invisible to the ASCII result. I would suggest re-validating your base64 not use the base64 encoder on Mac. If that gets denied for the same HTTP 401 error you were seeing in Hygieia, this is a large problem of your implementation of Jira not allowing for basic authentication. You would ultimately have 2 options at that point: 1) Contact your Jira admin and ask them to enable nosso option of authentication; 2) Update the JiraFeatureCollector to use token-based authentication (token or OAuth2.0). The latter may be the only option. Please let me know how this goes for you. — You are receiving this because you were mentioned. Thank you for your patience and contribution!! amp5208 220623892 For those that come here after the merged fix is implemented, it is important to note that the "ghost" `\n` return carriage that is included in a base64 encoded string on a Mac is avoidable easily by using the Mac implementation of `echo` correctly. Instead of the following command: ``` bash echo username:password | base64 ``` ... Use this command: ``` bash echo -n username:password | base64 ``` The `-n` option explicitly tells the Mac implementation of echo to not print the trailing new line character. amp5208

column2:
This commit adds containers for chat-ops and sonar.  It also modified the poms so you can do mvn docker:build from the root.  

To make it easier for people to download the project I have added containers for test versions of sonar & a jenkins to provide test data to drive the sonar and cucumber collectors.  Longer term we can use these containers to enhance the automated testing of these collectors in the the travis build. 

Note there is an older pull request for #169, I think this should be obsolete now with this commit.

Here are the issues addressed that can be closed with this pull:
#306 - Updated version of jacoco to make it compatible with Sonar Reference
#305 - Added container for Sonar
#239 - Created containers to provide examples for sonar & cucumber
#227 - added container for chat-ops
#169 - Updated docs for docker / docker-compose, changed build to handle docker:build target in the root pom
- cleaned up pom formats with new plugins for docker  
- TODO: today creating the containers is optional, we should consider making part of the package target  
- Note: Disalbed one test for full urls in the .md files, as I wanted to explain how to test the GIT collector using the Hygieia url

Here is a screenshot of how it looks with the demo data once this is merged and you follow the instructions in the Setup doc.

![screenshot 2016-02-09 10 39 48](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/14372687/12927162/86a35720-cf1b-11e5-9808-652efffd78e3.png)

When the pageSize default is exceeded, the resulting payload can take longer than the default socket timeout of 20000ms.  Adjusting this default would help with the larger datasets coming back from jira.

The result of the default is a timeout exception:

`
No result was available from Jira unexpectedly - defaulting to blank response. The reason for this fault is the following:java.net.SocketTimeoutException
`
column5: jira-feature-collector: Allow for a custom timeout for large datasets
column12: 181908163 @xeon22 , Actually, this would obviously be preferable. However, the collector is now using the JRJC. To my knowledge, the newest version of the JRJC does not have a timeout setting override. If you know of an override option for this, outside of overriding the entire class, please let me know, and I will gladly update. amp5208 195478653 @tabladrum , As mentioned in the above comment, socket timeout overrides are not an option for the Jira collector's JRJC. However, using the default pageSize settings, implemented in a previous merge, will resolve this issue. I recommend closing this issue, pending any further questions from @xeon22 . amp5208

column2: When the property is set, it is essentially ignored and the default of 1000 is used.

column2:
Trying to run sonar against our own build to create test/sample data for the dashboard I got an error, to fix this I have to change the version of jacoco.

Error: [ERROR] Failed to execute goal org.sonarsource.scanner.maven:sonar-maven-plugin:3.0.1:sonar (default-cli) on project Hygieia: Unable to read /Users/jaz/work/Hygieia/api/target/jacoco.exec: Incompatible version 1007. -> [Help 1]

I found this on the cloudless site Reference: https://cloudbees.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/205074234-SonarQube-reporting-is-failing-with-a-jacoco-error-Incompatible-version-1007

 This problems comes from an incompatibility in jacoco data produced by your build in version 0.7.5 that SonarQube cannot read with Jacoco 0.7.4. More details:

Issue
StackOverflow
To fix the issue you need to generate your coverage data with Jacoco 0.7.4.

If you are using Apache Maven to produce them replace

 org.jacoco:jacoco-maven-plugin:prepare-agent

``by

 org.jacoco:jacoco-maven-plugin:0.7.4.201502262128:prepare-agent
column5: jacoco 0.7.5 is not compatible with sonar - error 1007

column2:
I have a proposal.  As I was about to add containers for the remaining collectors, I realized the number is growing and everyone may not want to run all of them when the run docker-compose.

Does anyone know a pattern in docker-compose for this, I was unable to find one.

PROPOSAL: I have a proposal that we add an option "DISABLE_COLLECTOR" which can be set on any collector in the docker-cmpose.overrider.yml, if set then the collector will exit but give a very verbose explanation of why it was exited and how to enable it by modifying the docker-compose files.

I will work on this approach unless I get other feedback from the team.

        HudsonCollector protoType = new HudsonCollector();

column2:
When running the collector in a container localhost is mapped to http://10.0.2.2 (this is how docker handles the special case of local host it it is natted to that address).

So the URLS from jerkins have to be adjusted to work in your locally browser by changing 10.0.2.2 back to localhost.

Note: the 'view test job' link in the jerkins-cucumber collector works.

Now getting stuck on another issue - Fixed based on proxy issue #292 #293 aboe026 178819490 @apb66 , if you are having difficulty running the new versions of the Jira/VersionOne feature collector, please let me know. The pull request fix that you are referring to allows the use of no proxy, unauthenticated proxy, and an authenticated proxy. Also, there are additional properties required to be set at runtime with the Jira collector, which can be found below (from the README.md): 
# In Jira, general IssueType IDs are associated to various "issue"
# attributes. However, there is one attribute which this collector's
# queries rely on that change between different instantiations of Jira.
# Please provide the name value reference to your instance's IssueType for
# the lowest level of Issues (e.g., "user story") specific to your Jira
# instance.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's IssueType Name
# listings via the following URI:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issuetype/.  It is listed as
# attribute "name" in the JSON response.
feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "sprint" or "timebox" details,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your
# instance of Jira. Note: You can retrieve your instance's sprint data field name
# via the following URI, and look for a package name com.atlassian.greenhopper.service.sprint.Sprint;
# your custom field name describes the values in this field:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName=customfield_10007
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "super story" or "epic" back-end ID,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's epic ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has a super issue (e.g., epic) tied to it; your custom field name describes the
# epic value you expect to see, and is the only field that does this for a given issue:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_10400
#Core Artifacts
# These arrays of status mappings must be completed in order for custom source system statuses to be providable by
# Hygieia.  Currently, Hygieia only maps to the following 3 status mappings:  to do, doing, and done.  You can find
# all available issue status mappings by going to your instance's version of the following API call:
# http://fake.jira.com/rest/api/2/status/.  Your statuses are listed in the JSON response as "name."
feature.todoStatuses[0]=
feature.doingStatuses[0]=
feature.doneStatuses[0]=

181082435 Hi @oshingc 

please find below information, hope this helps :

1) while you sign up for the dashboard authentication would create. (creates Instantly)
2) While you start the API the feature, scope are created. (creates Instantly)
3) once you start creating new dashboard dashboard item gets saved . (creates Instantly)
4) saving the widgets, components would created. (creates Instantly)
5) once you run the collector , collector would saved, (it would take time depending upon the corn details ex : 2 minutes or so)
6) once you save any Job (JIRA-COLLECTOR ) in your case, it would create respective collections in collector items get saved in DB. (it would take time depending upon data present for that particular JIRA project depending upon the sprint/issue count ex : 2 minutes or so)

column2:
As mentioned by user @oshingc, there is a bug in the proxy / auth proxy string validation with the Jira collector that needs to be resolved.  If a user has not set a proxy, but their property file has the proxy / auth proxy props set as blank, or not there at all, the tool will currently throw a URI syntax or null pointer exception, as indicated in the following issue:  https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/292

This has now been fixed.  Please validate and merge as soon as possible.  I have also wrote additional test cases to cover these scenarios for Jira connections.
column12: 176362649 Thank you @oshingc. I have just pushed an update with the style suggestions from @tabladrum and @jdamick above. I also included additional connectivity checks for Jira. Please validate once more for your configuration, if you are able. Thank you! amp5208 176372822 It's working @amp5208 oshingc 176376604 I can pull in Guava and use the Strings package for this, so long as it passes the same tests. I will push with an update if it passes tests. Correction: Because the logic for the Guava class appears to only do Null OR Empty, those checkers do not work for me in this case, because I am negating the check (!) and require an AND. For this reason, I think that I have to use the POJO checkers - please validate. I was avoiding throwing null pointers and rather handle... but let me see what I can do. Edit: The Jira JRJC package that I am using requires me to test for URISyntaxException. I cannot avoid it here. amp5208 176471252 Updated based on suggestions by @tabladrum and @jdamick . Pending review. Tests pass and all cases set before this commit should work the same. @oshingc , Please validate your proxy scenario once more. amp5208 178059401 I have also pushed an important fix related to jira connection timeouts under production load. Please accept this pull request to also get this fix. (Note: I have also merged updates from upstream master with this latest commit to avoid merge conflicts) amp5208 176318289 I am not using the URI constructors prior to my local constructor to support backwards compatibility. However, let me try again and I will push an update. amp5208 176336661 I will switch to .isNullOrEmpty() Correction: I will use .isEmpty and leave a != null check, as it appears that there is no String.isNullOrEmpty() method in Java: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/8476588/java-equivalent-of-c-sharp-string-isnullorempty-and-string-isnullorwhitespace That section runs no matter what the user sets in their property file, and is run by the local clients. For this reason, I have to validate all scenarios. Did you have a suggestion on a better implementation here? amp5208 176352466 != null definitely catch the case of a property with no value I tested that when proxyUrl was empty. column2: I have refactored the entire JiraFeatureCollector based on @jdamick and PMD automated feedback. I have also re-wired the whole transformation and client layer to work with the Jira Atlasssian JRJC library, which ultimately makes heavy use of Jira's domain object model (as opposed to raw HTTP calls and JSON transformation). Please fully review my code and provide feedback. I would also explicitly like feedback in a section that I could not remove all PMD errors on: StoryDataClientImpl.java, line 84-86. Although this section is working and tested and has been refactored as stated above, I cannot reduct overall complexity of the method, because full domain object model translation of hierarchical issues is inherently complex. Note: Please do not fully merge this code until internal functional testing passes early next week. I will post here when functional tests have passed.

`var CollectorItemIds = [];`

`CollectorItems.push(form.collectoritemid2.value)`
`var postobj = {`
`CollectorItemId:[form.collectoritemid1.value,form.collectoritemid2.value],`

`}`

com.capitalone.dashboard.util.Constants
com.capitalone.dashboard.repository.ScopeOwnerRepository
com.capitalone.dashboard.model.ScopeOwnerCollectorItem

Thanks in advance for your help.

When running mvn clean install package as sudo, I would get an error saying bower install cannot be run with sudo. I had to append --allow-root to the argument in /UI/pom.xml in order to get bower to install and the mvn clean install package to complete successfullly:

``` xml
<execution>
    <id>bower install</id>
    <goals>
        <goal>bower</goal>
    </goals>
    <configuration>
        <arguments>install --allow-root</arguments>      <!-- added --allow-root to argument -->
    </configuration>
</execution>
```

Hope you are doing the following steps. I had tough time setting up the dashboard. I deleted dashboarddb in mongodb and recreated them again. 
After this, 

Scaling Agile India
DevOps with Anadi Misra 
1. Build the entire application from root 
   change to directory D:\Hygieia-master 
   execute the following mvn clean install package 

2.change to directory D:\Hygieia-master\api
    execute java -jar target\api.jar --spring.config.name=api --spring.config.location=dashboard.properties
    api monitoring starts

3.change to directory D:\Hygieia-master\UI

I found the issue. For some reason, the 'serve' command wasn't being run. I had to modify gulpfile and add it in the function runSequence:

gulp.task('build', function(callback) {
    runSequence('clean', ['assets', 'themes', 'fonts', 'js', 'views', 'test-data', 'serve'], 'html', callback);
});
 jamesjlee

There was a recent update with the newest master of the code which requires that you add the following 3 properties to your Jira properties file, depending on your specific Jira instance's configuration: 
. . .
# In Jira, general IssueType IDs are associated to various "issue"
# attributes. However, there is one attribute which this collector's
# queries rely on that change between different instantiations of Jira.
# Please provide a numerical ID reference to your instance's IssueType for
# the lowest level of Issues (e.g., "user story") specific to your Jira
# instance.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's IssueType ID
# listings via the following URI:  https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issuetype/
feature.jiraIssueTypeId=7
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "sprint" or "timebox" details,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your
# instance of Jira. Note: You can retrieve your instance's sprint data field name
# via the following URI, and look for a package name com.atlassian.greenhopper.service.sprint.Sprint;
# your custom field name describes the values in this field:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName=customfield_10007
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "super story" or "epic" back-end ID,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's epic ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has a super issue (e.g., epic) tied to it; your custom field name describes the
# epic value you expect to see, and is the only field that does this for a given issue:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_10400
. . .
Please let me know if after providing the correct values for these properties you are still having the issue noted above. amp5208 174480477 @amp5208 Do you've any doc on how to populate the above values.. Hygieia allows creation of a new username with less than 3 characters, however the login field validator expects a username to be at least 4.

When logging in with the valid 3 character user, the error message is: "Please fill all the form fields correctly". This message isn't helpful at all.

Either validate that a new user is at least 4 characters, or allow less than 4 characters when logging in.

column12:
218492727 @manjunath2008 , Please follow up and let me know if you have been successful in validating the following information: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/266#issuecomment-215733119 amp5208 227211031 Hi, Is the Remaining Estimate sums for stories field is the accumulated value per end-user? Or is it across the active sprint ? ashnaa 227211734 I am not able to get all the stories in my active sprint in Hygiea. Any pointers will be of help . ashnaa 227522949 @ashnaa , Thank you for reaching out. The sums are based on accumulated value per team / active sprint. Additionally, a new version of Hygieia's feature widget was released recently that included Kanban/Scrum simultaneous support (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/606). Please pull the latest code and try with the new configuration. Note that the properties required to run the collector have slightly changed - check the updated feature collector README for details. amp5208 270176204 Please use the latest master - a lot of enhancements and fixes have been made to feature widget. tabladrum 172063603 @cfmaley , thank you for reaching out regarding your Jira Feature question. Currently, the "features in progress" content on the FeatureWidget are designed to pull the time-estimate located in the Jira out-of-the-box field called . This is then transformed in the following way so that the numbers are manageable on the display: 
// sEstimate, in seconds, converted to hours, rounded down:
// 8 hours = 1 day; 5 days = 1 week
String hours = "";
long seconds = 0;
try {
       seconds = (long) fields.get("timeestimate");
       hours = Integer.toString((int) (seconds / 3600));
       feature.setsEstimate(TOOLS.sanitizeResponse(hours));
       } catch (Exception e) {
              feature.setsEstimate("0");
       }
Once data is transformed, "in progress" estimates are assumed based on the Jira statusCategory field, which is configured based on your Jira screen's workflow configuration. You must have a statusCategory called "In Progress" - This can be modified by a user with Project Administrative access. The following is the precise MongoDB query being used in code to get this information: 
@Query(value = " {'sTeamID' : ?0 , $and : [{'isDeleted' : 'False'} , {'sState' : 'Active'}] , $or : [{'sStatus' : 'In Progress'} , {'sStatus' : 'Waiting'} , {'sStatus' : 'Impeded'}] , $and : [{'sSprintID' : {$ne : null}} , {'sSprintBeginDate' : {$lte : ?1}} , {'sSprintEndDate' : {$gte : ?1}}]}, $orderby: { 'sStatus' :-1 }", fields = "{'sStatus': 1,'sEstimate' : 1}")
    List getSprintBacklogInProgress(String sTeamID, String currentISODateTime);
Please also note that the newest code in master allows for some custom configuration based on your Jira instance. You should also provided the following property values based on your instance's configuration: 
. . .
# In Jira, general IssueType IDs are associated to various "issue"
# attributes. However, there is one attribute which this collector's
# queries rely on that change between different instantiations of Jira.
# Please provide a numerical ID reference to your instance's IssueType for
# the lowest level of Issues (e.g., "user story") specific to your Jira
# instance.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's IssueType ID
# listings via the following URI:  https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issuetype/
feature.jiraIssueTypeId=7
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "sprint" or "timebox" details,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your
# instance of Jira. Note: You can retrieve your instance's sprint data field name
# via the following URI, and look for a package name com.atlassian.greenhopper.service.sprint.Sprint;
# your custom field name describes the values in this field:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName=customfield_10007
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "super story" or "epic" back-end ID,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's epic ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has a super issue (e.g., epic) tied to it; your custom field name describes the
# epic value you expect to see, and is the only field that does this for a given issue:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_10400
. . .
Please let me know if you have any additional questions and if this issue can be resolved. amp5208 195477808 @tabladrum , This issue can be closed, as it was resolved on a previous merge. @cfmaley, please confirm if you have any open questions related to this issue. amp5208 209353088 Hi All, Can anyone please tell me how is the Done value in Hygieia dashboard is being computed. Thanks & Regards Manjunath manjunath2008 209667297 @manjunath2008 , Thank you for reaching out regarding your question. Currently, the Done value is calculated using either the Detail Estimate value (VersionOne) or the Remaining Estimate value (Jira) summed and rounded-down for any stories mapped to the following statuses: Done, Accepted. Let me know if you need more specific details. amp5208 210585400 Hi, Thanks for the response. I am using Jira collector, I have couple of questions 1) Can you please tell me what information is Jira widget in the dashboard is displaying. 2) What does numeric value above Total, WIP, Done indicate Thanks & Regards Manjunath manjunath2008 213070234 Hi, @amp5208 can you please answer these questions. Thanks & Regards Manjunath.V manjunath2008 215733119 @manjunath2008 , Thank you for following-up. I will answer your questions below: 1. _Can you please tell me what information is Jira widget in the dashboard is displaying._ The feature widget will display Jira's **Remaining Estimate sums for stories** of a given active team/sprint combo selected by the end-user under the following status categories: **All Active (_Total_), In Progress (_WIP_), Done**. As Remaining Estimate is depleted, the sums will also deplete. These are not counts of stories, but instead based on the out-of-the-box Jira burn-down features on issues-type-story. See my answer above for more detail: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/266#issuecomment-209667297 2. _What does numeric value above Total, WIP, Done indicate_ See the answer I provided above. Let me know if you have any further questions. amp5208 218129343 @tabladrum : In Jira feature collector I am facing a problem while passing issueType ID, I have passed strory as IssueType Id in application.prop and I am receiving objects for bug, support and sub-tasks along with story. Could you please share any documentation related to this collector? ghouspasha 218492444 @ghouspasha , Thank you for reaching out. Please make sure that your property is listed precisely as follows: ``` properties feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story ``` Let me know if you are still seeing issues after ensuring this configuration. All other configuration details are listed in the [README](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/jira-feature-collector/README.md), although I will be simplifying the configuration details shortly. amp5208 218492727 @manjunath2008 , Please follow up and let me know if you have been successful in validating the following information: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/266#issuecomment-215733119 amp5208 227211031 Hi, Is the Remaining Estimate sums for stories field is the accumulated value per end-user? Or is it across the active sprint ? ashnaa 227211734 I am not able to get all the stories in my active sprint in Hygiea. Any pointers will be of help . ashnaa 227522949 @ashnaa , Thank you for reaching out. The sums are based on accumulated value per team / active sprint. Additionally, a new version of Hygieia's feature widget was released recently that included Kanban/Scrum simultaneous support (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/606). Please pull the latest code and try with the new configuration. Note that the properties required to run the collector have slightly changed - check the updated feature collector README for details. amp5208 270176204 Please use the latest master - a lot of enhancements and fixes have been made to feature widget. tabladrum

column2: I have beefed up integration/unit testing for the feature widget APIs and the repository Core artifacts used by both API and collectors, proving the issue, and thus proving the fix. I have also ensured that this runs on my machine with the issue resolved with $query. Note: We are still pending functional testing, because we have to stand-up a new CloudFormation to do it - do not fully merge this pull request until after automated functional testing passes.

Security analysis: Currently it supports Fortify. We could not publish the collector as it uses some non-Open Source client libraries that comes with Fortify. For your information, I was unable to connect to MongoDB through Robomongo. Hence I changed the schema version to 3 as per instructions in http://stackoverflow.com/questions/29006887/mongodb-cr-authentication-failed . I am not sure if this had any impact. I had setup Hygieia in September 2015 as well but even then UCD widget was empty, although MongoDB was using Schema version 3.

PLease help. Thanks in advance.
