column2:
This enhancement enables the use and running of tests leveraging the embedded MongoDB test packages when an authenticated proxy is required.  This will also work with existing, non-authenticated proxy settings, as the logic for that option will run independent of the logic for authenticated proxies.

I also updated the Setup.md readme to include explicit instructions for how to configure both an authenticated and non-authenticated proxy.
column5: Enabled authenticated proxy configuration for embedded MongoDB tests
column12:
165869677 I'll fix the exception case, the formatting issues and resubmit a commit again.
the removal of scope "test" is actually fixing a runtime issue with VersionOneFeatureCollector, stopping it from actually running.  If you build on your machine with that change, you will see that you will now get the expected "$query" error that i am ultimately fixing.  It is required for that fix.
 amp5208
165875338 I have just committed the requested changes.  @jdamick , Please review and let me know if anything further should be done regarding the embedded mongodb proxy authentication enhancement
 amp5208
165899790 I see what you mean - i'm swallowing the exception instead of handling it before it ever happens.  I'll recommit next week with the changes you have suggested.  Thanks again for the input!
 amp5208
166333750 I have submitted some changes to the committed embedded MongoDB test case which check for authenticated proxy user info content, based on feedback from @jdamick .  I have left one catch for malformed exceptions, which does not entirely swallow the exception, as it prints a log of important information, but i have removed the swallowing NPE.  instead, i replaced this with a double-IF block that uses the tokenizer's built-in boolean check to see if more tokens are available before actually setting them.  this should cover for the use case that the username is blank (assumes then that password is also blank), and if the username is filled but the password is blank.  both cases will skip then to the proxy-only (non-auth) section.

Let me know if you have any remaining issues and i would be happy to fix them.
 amp5208
166336958 thanks
 jdamick
165598126 I can make those modifications; however, please note, as Hygieia is currently written in master will not work with an authenticated proxy - this fix does resolve the issue, but I can make it pull out the username password from the default proxy variable strings.

Please do not close this PR, as I can commit an update directly to this PR.

Thank you for the feedback!
 amp5208
165845523 I have pushed an update to this commit which utilizes the feedback that you provided, @jdamick .  Please review and let me know if you have any additional thoughts or concerns.  I also added a pom fix that was causing an issue to VersionOneFeatureCollector that @tabladrum / @amitmawkin saw the other day, and fixed a method declaration issue with the Core's Component's class (using a 'replace' instead of a 'put', which also performs a replace action).
 amp5208
165859805 @softwareklinic, can you confirm if the updated changes in this pull request will negatively/positively affect a *.pac proxy script, as you have noted as a concern in an earlier pull request?
 amp5208
165868987 pac files aren't used, this only for env variables.
 jdamick
165869677 I'll fix the exception case, the formatting issues and resubmit a commit again.
the removal of scope "test" is actually fixing a runtime issue with VersionOneFeatureCollector, stopping it from actually running.  If you build on your machine with that change, you will see that you will now get the expected "$query" error that i am ultimately fixing.  It is required for that fix.
 amp5208
165875338 I have just committed the requested changes.  @jdamick , Please review and let me know if anything further should be done regarding the embedded mongodb proxy authentication enhancement
 amp5208
165899790 I see what you mean - i'm swallowing the exception instead of handling it before it ever happens.  I'll recommit next week with the changes you have suggested.  Thanks again for the input!
 amp5208
166333750 I have submitted some changes to the committed embedded MongoDB test case which check for authenticated proxy user info content, based on feedback from @jdamick .  I have left one catch for malformed exceptions, which does not entirely swallow the exception, as it prints a log of important information, but i have removed the swallowing NPE.  instead, i replaced this with a double-IF block that uses the tokenizer's built-in boolean check to see if more tokens are available before actually setting them.  this should cover for the use case that the username is blank (assumes then that password is also blank), and if the username is filled but the password is blank.  both cases will skip then to the proxy-only (non-auth) section.

Let me know if you have any remaining issues and i would be happy to fix them.
 amp5208
166336958 thanks
 jdamick

column2:
Current version of Hygieia does not allow for running tests (and thus building) via Maven from behind an authenticated proxy.  This update includes the ability for code to be fully built/tested/run from behind a corporate authentication proxy.  This will also allow for non-authenticated proxies to still be used as per normal.

Also, I updated the Setup readme to clearly indicate how a developer should configure a local proxy if they need to, given this enhancement.
column5: Added capability for tests to run behind an authenticated corporate proxy
column12:
165568333 The HTTP/S_PROXY variables should look like:

```
HTTP_PROXY=http://<id>:<passwd>@proxy.somewhere:80
```

So we shouldnt added HTTP_AUTHxxx, etc. as this breaks users and is non-standard.
 jdamick
165568579 Some of use auto proxy scripts… would that work as well?

Reply-To: capitalone/Hygieia <reply@reply.github.com<mailto:reply@reply.github.com>>

So we shouldnt added HTTP_AUTHxxx, etc. as this breaks users..

Please confirm if this works for your use case.

column12:
165276383 Absolutely, it makes perfect sense.

We were discussing during the team meeting today about the same,, since looks like in the current state of affairs, the dashboard can track
1 Branch of code… for any given project at this point… now if we want to track 2-3 branches of the same project… or 2-3 projects… with 3-4 container / branch it would be soon be a mess.

We need to look at 2 things
1.  From infrastructure perspective – how soon we can have the env up and running
2.  How do we manage/design it for future – since soon you will see lot of people adapting this tool and then how do you make this manageable for complex corporate applications.

We were thinking maybe a single container with all collectors + api + ui would be a good option for a given branch.. We can have tracking for any single branch of code up and running quickly…

Let me know your thoughts.

Keyur

column12:
165277288 Looks like these urls are obsolete... is there any on the new atlassian site? softwareklinic 165500094 Allow me to clarify: You need to replace the "jira.com" host name part of those URLs with your fully qualified Jira host name. I have edited the comment above to reflect this. amp5208 169163696 This issue will be fixed in the newest pull request regarding Feature Widget updates, as you will now be able to specify your Jira instance's custom "user story" issue type ID at deploy-time via properties file amp5208 172060543 @softwareklinic, this issue has now been resolved, as of the most recent update to master. Please pull the newest code and evaluate. Be sure to also update the following 3 property settings based on your Jira instance's configuration: 
. . .
# In Jira, general IssueType IDs are associated to various "issue"
# attributes. However, there is one attribute which this collector's
# queries rely on that change between different instantiations of Jira.
# Please provide a numerical ID reference to your instance's IssueType for

Looks like this tool has great potential and it has caused some initial pain and frustration when trying out... There are some steps on how to build/install, configure docker container etc.. but what is missing is end-2-end configuration.. say for a given version of Jira, Jenkins, Stash, Sonar, etc... with URL examples, complete details on how to configure this tool... without missing any heartbeat

I have started to compile a word document with screenshots... and will try to post it here... but currently stuck with collectors not collecting and displaying data in UI except JENKINS... most stash/bitbucket/git/jira collectors are having some or the other issue.. most likely it is due to lack of knowledge or steps on how to configure those seamlessly.

I plan on following up with this item as soon as possible and as soon as priorities allow me. To verify, however, can you confirm with me your data within your MongoDB store? Are you seeing data that should other wise map to the following scenario: An active Issue mapped to a status, mapped to an active Project, that is mapped to an active, in-progress Sprint? To validate this in the data, please check you feature MongoDB collection based on your Jira collector ID. amp5208 195453648 @SubramaniMurthy, This issue has been continued in the following Issue post: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/276. Assuming that your access is sufficient to pull all Jira data, the following error message: 
There was a problem retrieving or parsing data from the local repository while retrieving a max change date

It worked fine.

206945783 BINGO.... Thanks a lot. Its working now.
The problem was it was referring to another db. 

Configuration was
#Database Name 
spring.data.mongodb.database=dashboardb

And i changed to 
#Database Name 
dbname=dashboardb

It worked fine.

163775832 That fixed it thanks softwareklinic.  Changed 3 methods from private to protected.

```
protected void log(String marker, long start) {
    log(marker, start, null);
}

protected void log(String text, long start, Integer count) {
    long end = System.currentTimeMillis();
    String elapsed = ((end - start) / 1000) + "s";
    String token2 = "";
    String token3;
    if (count == null) {
        token3 = StringUtils.leftPad(elapsed, 30 - text.length() );
    } else {
        String countStr = count.toString();
        token2 = StringUtils.leftPad(countStr, 20 - text.length() );
        token3 = StringUtils.leftPad(elapsed, 10 );
    }
    LOG.info(text + token2 + token3);
}

protected void logBanner(String instanceUrl) {
    LOG.info("------------------------------");
    LOG.info(instanceUrl);
    LOG.info("------------------------------");
```

column2:
For hygieia 2.0 it has been proposed that we change hygieia from a snapshot in time to a real-time dashboard that incorporates dev pipeline graphs along with operational graphs.

Desired:
- [ ] near real-time dev pipeline dashboard metrics
- [ ] near real-time operational dashboard metrics
- [ ] customizable widgets with customizable queries
- [ ] alerting based on defined criteria
- [ ] pre-baked dashboards / templates (to match current hygieia functionality)

To get there I think we should take the following steps:
- [ ] change our DB to influxdb, which will be a better fit for our needs and give us integration flexibility
- [ ] change our UI components to be grafana
- [ ] build out dashboard templates for our canned dashboards
- [ ] let grafana handle altering (when it's done: https://github.com/grafana/grafana/issues/2209)
- [ ] update the collectors to send metrics into influxdb
- [ ] migrate existing data from mongo to influx

So basically hygieia becomes a project that houses various collectors and adds some opinionated templates to grafana/influxdb.

cc/ @tabladrum

column12:
162278786 Fix for this on MAC OSX is to increase the limits 

To check open file limits

You can check these with:

```
sysctl kern.maxfiles
sysctl kern.maxfilesperproc
```

You can increase the limits (at your own risk) with:

```
sysctl -w kern.maxfiles=20480 (or whatever number you choose)
sysctl -w kern.maxfilesperproc=18000 (or whatever number you choose)
```

column12:
220117306 @okram999 :  No problem!  And actually, it looks like you're effectively building and running Hygieia's UI by itself.  I think the issue here was that you were missing the global Gulp install, used for cleaning, building, deploying and orchestrating the UI.  Please simply try and re-run the global Maven build now; I would expect that it will work for you.

If you are still failing the UI portion of the parent Maven build, I will defer to another colleague for assistance.

_**Note:**  You are only receiving proxy errors at run time because you have not started the API.  Once started, you will not longer receive proxy errors and the UI will be full-functional._

_**Additional Note:**  Be sure to also install MongoDB and follow the read-me [instructions for MongoDB configuration/installation](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/Setup.md#database).  The API will fail to deploy without an installation of MongoDB 3.0 running._

161514971 @amitmawkin Not sure if it fits our need. I was looking for something like [registering the bean/implementation based on condition](https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/current/reference/html/boot-features-developing-auto-configuration.html#boot-features-property-conditions). This way we can pass a property with value, say git.web.host.service.name=stash and every client should have this annotation with the expected value, eg: for Stash client it should be something like `@ConditionalOnProperty(prefix = "git.web.host.service.name", havingValue = "stash")`.

Also I see lots of code here is duplicated and also expect more duplication in future as we add more services (eg: gitlab and so). So it is worth to spend some time to see how we can reuse the most. In my opinion I only expect the implementation of clients to be different and the rest are going to be the same. So would suggest to have multi-module project ([explained in the previous comment](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/189#issuecomment-161412018)). This way still we can have separate collectors and reuse the common code.

But anyways this topic should not stop this PR. We can still merge it and the restructuring/refactor can be done in a separate PR.
 srid99
161676120 i agree about the reuse and eliminate the duplicate code, but i think we should opt for something simpler rather than a lot of spring annotations that makes the code hard to follow & maintain.
 jdamick

161376023 @jdamick @tabladrum As discussed in gitter I can spend some time this weekend to write unit test. Just to be clear, I will be writing unit test for classes GitCollectorTask, DefaultStashClient, DefaultBitbucketClient. The other classes doesn't seem to be interesting, if not let me know.

161382288 So that's going to be integration test then :+1: 
 srid99
161390246 I had a quick look at the PR and I have some questions, maybe @dianewalls can help me understanding it,

There are 2 GitClient implementations available, one for BitBucket and another for Stash. The BitBucket client is annotated with @Component and Stash client is not. Based on my Spring knowledge (which is not that good :P), when Spring wires the dependencies for GitCollectorTask it will use BitBucket client and not the Stash client (since Spring will not recognize Stash as a component). Is that correct or am I missing something ?
 srid99
161407026 @srid99 you are right. I just remove the @component on stash client because I want to make the Bitbucket client work. I didn't want to make another collector because the only difference is the client. So maybe then we can have two threads
 dianewalls
161412018 @dianewalls I understand but I think we have to make a decision before we merge this PR (or not).

@amitmawkin @tabladrum @jdamick What is your opinion on this ? If we like to have separate collectors for each hosting service (github, stash, bitbucket and so on) then I would suggest to split (stash and bitbucket) into 2 collectors so that at least it is consistent even though they both are from same Company.

The other option would be to have one collector let's say git-scm-collector and provide a way to tell the collector which client should be used. Or if you still want it to be separate collectors we can make git-scm-collector a multi-module project which has core, github-scm-collector, stash-scm-collector, bitbucket-scm-collector. The core can contain the spring-boot stuff which can be added as a dependency to the scm-collectors where the scm-collectors have the implementation for the client.

Like to hear your opinion. And I am also sorry if in anyway I am blocking this PR :) I really want to use it for our project and I can spend some time along with @dianewalls to get this refactoring. If that is fine.
 srid99
161414127 Whats the difference between the two clients? Just some api endpoint patterns are different? Current Github collector handles both Enterprise and the Public even though the api urls are different. Can something similar be done? 
 tabladrum
161416159 Did a quick comparison and Yes there is a difference between the payloads/responses. Eg: in stash the scmRevisionNumber is mapped to json field 'id' and for bitbucket it is mapped to field 'hash'. To be precise the difference is with 3 fields, revision number, author and commit timestamp. So it needs a different client unless we use one client and make decision based on the field name eg: id or hash to decide if the response is from stash or bitbucket. But this sounds like a code smell to me :)
 srid99

column12:
154526124 @jdamick check the updates please. thanks.
 tabladrum
155215502 so now in really looking at this, i think we should do the following:
- change to sub-resources for security and anything inside the quality widget, it's a bit kludgy to have a switch statement in the resource handler
  - have an actual sub-resource for security, so that it has its own path & mock data json
- this includes updating the test resource to be under the quality as well

We should think about having sub-widgets for quality, or break them into full widgets.  They don't follow the pattern right of the others so it's going to be harder to maintain / add to later on.  

Also the json returned / entered to the db should be normalized, it seems that field names like:
`ncloc` & `test_success_density` are tool specific..   
 jdamick

column2: Fix all docs as related to issue #159

fixed version to be greater than the largest released component (versionone was 1.3.0)

added more logging, added version change script & cleaned up poms

I have Hygieia running on a VM and within the VM I used the docker-compose command to bring up the mongo, api and ui containers. They are all linked to each other and I am able to create a user online and to create a dashboard. When I did the `mvn install` within the GitHub collector directory it created a github collector jar file which I used the command `java -jar github-scm-collector-1.0.0.jar --spring.config.name=application` I created an application.properties file that is the same as the sample.properties file that was shown and I edited the file to have the mongodb credentials. When I run the java command I get the following errors:
2015-11-03 15:55:53,780 INFO  org.mongodb.driver.cluster - Exception in monitor thread while connecting to server 127.0.0.1:27017
com.mongodb.MongoSecurityException: Exception authenticating
    at com.mongodb.connection.NativeAuthenticator.authenticate(NativeAuthenticator.java:48) ~[mongo-java-driver-3.0.2.jar!/:na]
    at com.mongodb.connection.InternalStreamConnectionInitializer.authenticateAll(InternalStreamConnectionInitializer.java:99) ~[mongo-java-driver-3.0.2.jar!/:na]
    at com.mongodb.connection.InternalStreamConnectionInitializer.initialize(InternalStreamConnectionInitializer.java:44) ~[mongo-java-driver-3.0.2.jar!/:na]
    at com.mongodb.connection.InternalStreamConnection.open(InternalStreamConnection.java:115) ~[mongo-java-driver-3.0.2.jar!/:na]
    at com.mongodb.connection.DefaultServerMonitor$ServerMonitorRunnable.run(DefaultServerMonitor.java:127) ~[mongo-java-driver-3.0.2.jar!/:na]
    at java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:745) [na:1.7.0_85]
Caused by: com.mongodb.MongoCommandException: Command failed with error 18: 'auth failed' on server 127.0.0.1:27017. The full response is { "ok" : 0.0, "errmsg" : "auth failed", "code" : 18 }

I am not sure why I am unable to authenticate when I can use the mongo shell and use the exact same credentials and connect to the database. Is there something that I am missing?

In fact once I created a DB called 'dashboard' in MongoDB then it started working. I was able to create the dasboard widgets.

So the sample properties files are misleading.

144429601 I have a Dockerfile and a list of commands that seem to get it working. 
https://github.com/hughbrien/Hygieia/blob/patch-2/Dockerfile

docker build -t hygieia-base .
docker run -it -d  -p 3000:3000 -p 8080:8080  --name hygieia  hygieia-base /bin/bash;
docker exec -it hygieia  /bin/bash

Once inside of the 
mvn clean install package
cd ./UI
bower install --allow-root
cd ./api 
mvn install
nohup mongod --dbpath /Hygieia/data &

mongo
use 
db.createUser(
     {
       user: "dashboarduser",
       pwd: "1qazxSw2",
       roles: [
         {role: "readWrite", db: "dashboarddb"}
               ]
       })

db.createUser(
     {
       user: "sbrien",
       pwd: "password",
       roles: [
         {role: "readWrite", db: "dashboarddb"}
               ]
       })

cd /Hygieia 
nohup java -jar api/target/api.jar &

cd /Hygieia/UI
gulp serve 

Now we want to start all the Java Collector Services 
It appears that collectors must be run from with their respective <home> directories 
cd /Hygieia/GitHubSourceCodeCollector/target/
github-collector-1.0.0.jar

Several of the collectors have copy & pasted code for the http clients & processing code.  I'd like to see them share a common set of utils & clients.  I would suggest something like https://github.com/Netflix/feign with okhttp, such that the code would be more readable.

- [ ] Ability to record server responses - so that we can replay them for unit tests

column2:
Ability to run separate Docker containers for the API and the UI, similar to production layouts.

The API is using a tomcat container and the UI is using an nginx container
The docker images are part of the maven compile using spotify's docker plugin

``` bash
cd api
mvn clean package docker:build

cd ../UI
mvn clean package docker:build
```

This will create 2 containers for you, hygieia_api and hygieia_ui
You can now create a swarm, connect a docker or managed mongo, to run it all within a standard docker-machine

``` bash
docker run -h mongo -d --name mongo mongo:latest
docker run -h hygieia_api --link mongo:mongo -P -d --name hygieia_api hygieia_api
docker run -d -P -h hygieia_ui --name hygieia_ui --link hygieia_api:api hygieia_ui
```

hygieia_api expects a network link / alias called mongo
hygieia_ui expects a network link / alias called hygieia_api
column5: Docker containers for Hygieia and UI

column2:
Not showing the correct number of commits/contributors from Github.

As explained by tabladrum:
When the collector runs continuously, the numbers will be correct over 14 days. Each time (based on the cron setting) the collector runs, it fetches commits from lastupdated - 10 mins (randomly set) and discards the duplications while saving it.

Enhancement needed: For the first run, go back 14 days.
column12:
135840349 Working on it. Thanks for reporting the bug.
 tabladrum
136339694 Update: Github commit api by default returns 30 commits per request and sets the pagination information in the response header. It also limits the number of commit api requests to 60 per hour for unauthenticated user. For "busy" repo's on github.com, I see that we can possibly reach the limit easily. 
 tabladrum
136525898 @krismy93 Can you test github collector updated code from here: https://github.com/tabladrum/Hygieia
It now handles paging to handle default 30 per page commits.

Need to put in some comments and logs if it looks ok.
Caution: The api calls still are unauthenticated - and that will probably cause HTTP 403 once number of calls reaches 60 in an hour.  
 tabladrum
137476653 @krismy93 Can we close this?
 tabladrum
137480503 Yes. Thank you!

column2: The documentation says the following configuration: ``` sonar.metrics=ncloc,coverage,violations,critical_violations,major_violations,blocker_violations ``` However, this results in the following: (So, 0% coverage data). This is because the sonar metrics displayed in the UI is not the coverage, but the line coverage (line_coverage). It's confusing. Then, updating the configuration doesn't do anything. I add the metric line_coverage, and no line_coverage is added. The non-obvious fix for that is to run the following Mongo query: `db.code_quality.drop()` What are you ideas on that?
column12:

 krismy93
149743538 closing based on pull #107 
 jdamick
136429492 I am having this same issue. I am trying to get the % of coverage to show up. 
 krismy93
136438857 I was able to get the line coverage to show by:
1. Dropping the "code_quality" collection
2. Re-editing the application.properties file:
`sonar.metrics=ncloc,line_coverage,violations,critical_violations,major_violations,blocker_violations`
3. Re-starting the jar

![screen shot 2015-08-31 at 10 34 36 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5998068/9585505/3b8ae394-4fcc-11e5-8814-0e9101597ec7.png)
 krismy93
136513330 Hi @krismy93 , sorry to hear you had the same issue. I'll try to get into it this week and make a fix + pull request for this.
 bodiam
136520934 Thanks @bodiam 
To get all the widgets to display the relevant information the final application.properties had:
`sonar.metrics=ncloc,line_coverage,violations,critical_violations,major_violations,blocker_violations,sqale_index,test_success_density,test_failures,test_errors,tests`

This should probably be updated within the sample file.

According to my understanding, the UI will get some data from API, but it seems there is no any setting property for UI, my API port is 8080, When I access http://xxxxx/api/dashboard, I can see some dashboard json data, but When I config the build widget, there is no any build job to select. Jenkins collector is running well yqbjtu 158875766 Thank you! yqbjtu 166745556 Can we close this? tabladrum 166913713 I believe that this issue should still be marked as a future enhancement for enabling field customization for Hygieia (see my comment above). Otherwise, I would say this is closed, pending customer response. amp5208 167007748 you can close this. krismy93 136508737 @krismy93 , thank you for reaching out regarding your Jira question. Based on our Gitter conversation, I believe that you are seeing "0"s on your dashboard because you are using a non-standard / custom Jira field to pull story point estimates. Jira, by default, uses time based estimates using the timeestimate field, which is in business hours/days. However, in an effort to make this dashboard more usable for different DevOps architectures, certain custom fields should be configurable via a property setting. I believe that enabling field customization out of the box for Hygieia should be made a priority and should be added as an enhancement. @tabladrum , Please mark this as an enhancement; I may have already created a similar issue on here; if that is the case, please close that issue and mark this as an enhancement. amp5208 158875745 @krismy93, Do you know how to config the communication from UI to API. According to my understanding, the UI will get some data from API, but it seems there is no any setting property for UI, my API port is 8080, When I access http://xxxxx/api/dashboard, I can see some dashboard json data, but When I config the build widget, there is no any build job to select. Jenkins collector is running well yqbjtu 158875766 Thank you! yqbjtu 166745556 Can we close this? tabladrum 166913713 I believe that this issue should still be marked as a future enhancement for enabling field customization for Hygieia (see my comment above). Hi all,

Right now, the Hygieia code is using two build tools, Maven and Gradle, and I find it a bit confusing to know which one to use. The current documentation is just as confusing, since some of the documentation (for example, the main documentation) talks about Gradle, but the documentation of the sub projects talk about Maven. 

I can do a pull request, that's fine, but I'd like to know the general sentiment about getting rid of the Maven code.

135416882 @tabladrum You noted:

> Main issue we ran into was a good way to pass in Environment variable in the command line (gradlew)

Can you provide more info or a more concrete example? I'm another potential helper who would would like to see a Gradle build.
 dstine
135422244 Main issue: the API needs an environment variable DASHBOARD_PROP or a system variable dashboard.prop to be set to point to the properties file. 

Somehow this is not working with Gradlew command line. The API kept using default set hard coded in the API code. 

IDE issue with Eclipse: with gradle enabled, usual eclipse feature to run the API by context menu "Run on server" is no longer available. And running gradle task ran into the same issue with passing environment variable.

IDE issue with IntelliJ: same as passing the env variable via IntelliJ run config. Also tried with IntelliJ tomcat config - it overrides my machines Tomcat's setenv.sh ignoring any export I may have in there. 
 tabladrum
135432795 please see my response to #97 
 jdamick
135433893 move to #97 
 jdamick
135461095 Main issue: the API needs an environment variable DASHBOARD_PROP or a system variable dashboard.prop to be set to point to the properties file. 

Somehow this is not working with Gradlew command line. The API kept using default set hard coded in the API code. 

IDE issue with Eclipse: with gradle enabled, usual eclipse feature to run the API by context menu "Run on server" is no longer available. And running gradle task ran into the same issue with passing environment variable.

IDE issue with IntelliJ: same as passing the env variable via IntelliJ run config. Also tried with IntelliJ tomcat config - it overrides my machines Tomcat's setenv.sh ignoring any export I may have in there. 
 tabladrum
134564887 We removed the maven code, but some developers were not comfortable with Gradle, hence we decided to put maven back,  I will add instructions on main Readme for building via Maven, they were there if you look at the commit history , but were removed when gradle was introduced
 amitmawkin
134566949 Were there specific reasons why they were not comfortable with Gradle? Doing a `mvn clean install` or `gradle build` can hardly be the reason right?

We are experimenting with Hygieia too, and I don't care which build tool you use, but some of my colleagues are adding features, and are updating the pom. I use the Gradle version, and of course we run into the problems that only the pom.xml is updated. Also, right now the documentation is inconsistent: the main documentation talks about Gradle, while (some of?) the sub projects talk about Maven. Confusing at best, but it will make contributions a lot harder in regard for writing features and documentation.

I'm trying to make a point here to just have one build tool and deal with it :-). If it's Maven, fine, if it's Gradle, better, but having two is the worst scenario IMO.

I would just remove everything from Maven, and just add some clear documentation about Gradle. That's what I will also do for our local fork.
 bodiam
134575036 :+1: for removing Maven

Recently I had some problems (got NoSuchMethodError exceptions) with running the application from my IDE (IntelliJ) on analyzing the issue noticed that there were some mismatch with Spring versions. And understood that the actual cause for the issue is by mistake I enabled Gradle support (stupid mistake from my side). So all dependencies are added twice (from Maven and Gradle) and they are not in sync. To avoid such confusions and for maintenance sake, we should just stick with one build tool.

I prefer Gradle.
 srid99
134589934 I want to get Gradle working too and stay with one single build system. Want to make sure that everything works seamlessly irrespective of IDE used (Eclipse, IntelliJ etc). Command line worked great. Working through some issues with Eclipse setup. Once this is done, will switch to ONE build system. 
 tabladrum
134808188 Heads up: We will be staying with Maven. I will do a PR within 24 hrs to clean up and making all documents consistent.
 tabladrum

column2:
**Narrative:**

The current Jira collector only considers "teams" to be the Jira Project ~~; likewise, Jira only considers the out-of-the-box "Remaining Estimate" field for estimates.~~  Although this may be the case for most flat organizations, larger organizations may require a custom field option for setting Teams; respectively, the out of the box estimates field does not work for everyone.  I would suggest allowing a user to configure custom to their own process a field that sets where "Team" data exists~~; likewise, this should also exist for estimates.~~

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- [ ] Teams are configurable at runtime for the Jira Feature Collector, and thus configurable for the end-user on the widget display from drop-down filters
- [x] ~~Estimate fields are configurable at runtime for the Jira Feature Collector, and thus display on the widget for the end-user~~

**Use Case:**

```
# Teams
GIVEN the Hygieia Feature Widget
WHEN a user configures the widget for his/her team
THEN the "teams" available are from the custom organization configured by the specific implementation of Jira and the Hygieia Dashboard for his/her org needs
```

~~# Estimates
GIVEN:  A Jira Board configured with custom Estimate fields
WHEN:  An issue type story is created using a customized Estimate field
THEN:  The issue type story's Estimate value is applied to a running implementation of Hygieia's Feature Widget IF the custom Estimate field is mentioned at runtime.~~
column5: Request:  Jira Collector needs a dynamic option for setting "team" fields

131105131 The only place we have a password concept is the dashboard owner. Our initial version did not even have that - we believe all the information that are displayed on the dashboard should be transparent to everyone. The problem that we ran into was that PersonA could modify PersonB's dashboard. So, we introduced the owner concept just to make sure that does not happen.

Having said that, I already pushed some new API's and Encryption classes and am working on allowing real passwords (such as jenkins, jira passwords etc) to be stored encrypted.
